out_desc_tool: ORF measures a. student's ability to orally read a passage with precision. This measure has been recommended consistently due to its strong correlation with other more complicated measures of reading comprehension (Greenwood, Tapia, Abbott, & Walton, 2003) and because of its ease of administration (Hasbrouck & Tindal, 2005). For our pre- and posttesting,- students were first given a standardized instruction protocol, with 60 seconds to read from a single page of text. The ORF measures used were all narrative text. The assessor followed along as the student read, recording errors for misread, skipped, or unknown words. Words that the student corrected immediately after first reading incorrectly were not counted as errors.

out_desc_tool: Early Grade Reading Assessment Test EGRA (Gove, 2008). The development of EGRA began in October 2006, when United States Agency for International Development (USAID), through its EdData II proyect, contracted Research Triangle Institute (RTI) International to develop an instrument for assessing early grade reading. The objective was to help USAID partner countries begin the process of measuring, in a systematic way, how well children in the early grades of primary school are acquiring reading skills, and ultimately to spur more effective efforts to improve performance in this core learning skill.

out_desc_tool: Researchers at the local university created the items for the district-level mathematics tests and gathered validity evidence suggesting that the results are appropriate for use as a screener. Three tests were created for each grade level. The three equivalent tests are administered in the fall, winter, and spring, respectively. Items are aligned with the state content standards in mathematics at each grade, which recognize five domains in mathematics  calculations and estimations, measurement, geometry, statistics and probability, and algebraic relations. Researchers consulted state content standards and curriculum materials to develop grade-level-appropriate items that adequately represented grade­level content.

out_desc_tool: The ability test contains 20 items with multiplication problems up to 10 × 20. The test consists of ten items in the form of 6 × 7=, and ten in the form of a short story. The children are also asked to write down their solution procedure. The answers are scored as right or wrong, and the solution strategies used by each child are recorded. The ability test includes a total of 10 items beyond 10 × 10. As the students were taught only tasks below 10 × 10, these more difﬁcult items constituted a transfer measure. Transfer refers to the effects of prior learning on later learning in practice (Schopman, 1998).

out_desc_tool: The TOWRE (Torgesen et al., 1999) consists oftwo subtests  a sight-word efﬁciency section and a phonemic-decoding efﬁciency section. Both subtests provide raw scores, age equivalents, and grade equivalents, for students reading between the ﬁrst and the twelfth grade levels. For the purposes of this study, only the sight- word component of the test was administered. In this section, the students were asked to identify as many words as possible within a 45-second period from a list of sight words provided by the examiner. The results provided a standardized measure of word recognition in isolation.
